<div id="content_table" style="width: 866px;"   >
<br><br>
<h1 class="h1_blue_dark">Thesis Development</h1>

 
<table width="866px" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" cellpadding="5" border=0>
<tr><td>
<div>
<h1 class="h1_gray">Introduction</h1>
<br>
In many of your courses&#8212;such as English, history, psychology, and philosophy&#8212;you 
are asked to write essays arguing one point or another.  A good essay begins with a statement 
of purpose&#8212;a controlling idea which predicts 
and confines the subject you are covering in your essay.  This controlling idea, or thesis, 
is your essay's life and spirit, for without it, your chances of running amuck in your essay, 
of dragging your reader through a series of unrelated ideas, are more than increased&#8212;they are 
guaranteed.  In this GLA you will learn how to construct a good thesis statement.<br><br>
</div>
</td></tr>


<tr><td><table width="866px" class="border_green" border=0>
	<tr>
	<td><div>

<strong>By the end of this activity, you should be able to:</strong> <br><br>

	<ul class="c">
	<li>Define the concept of thesis statement</li>
	<li>Identify and contrast weak and strong thesis statements</li>
	<li>Narrow a thesis statement from general to specific</li>
	<li>Compose a coherent, unified thesis statement</li>
	</ul>

</div>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table></td></tr>

<tr><td><div>
<br><br>
<h1 class="h1_gray">Let's get started!</h1><br>

<strong>If at any time you need help, please ask a tutor.</strong><br><br>
</div></td></tr>
<!-- this is the steps table -->
<tr><td>
<table width="866px" border=0>
<tr><td width="80px" valign="top"><h1 class="h1_gray">Step 1: </h1></td>
<td valign="bottom"><div>First you'll need to make sure you have the handouts for this activity. 
If you don't, ask a tutor to help you.<br><br></div></td></tr>


<tr><td width="80px" valign="top"><h1 class="h1_gray">Step 2: </h1></td>
<td><div>Read these two handouts: "Thesis Development – Characteristics of Strong Thesis Statements" and 
"Thesis Development – Thesis Statement Criteria". 
<br><br></div></td></tr>


<tr><td width="80px" valign="top"><h1 class="h1_gray">Step 3: </h1></td>
<td><div>Watch this <a href="Thesis Development.ppt">PowerPoint presentation</a> on how to create strong thesis statements.
<br><br></div></td></tr>

<tr><td width="80px" valign="top"><h1 class="h1_gray">Step 4: </h1></td>
<td><div>Complete the exercises on the "Thesis Development" worksheet.  
Make sure to use the rubric provided to evaluate any thesis statement you write. (The rubric handout is called 
"Thesis Development – Thesis Statement Rubric".)<br><br>


STOP and review your worksheet with a tutor.
<br><br></div></td></tr>


<tr><td width="80px" valign="top"><h1 class="h1_gray">Step 5: </h1></td>
<td><div>Complete the quiz and self-reflection in the handouts.<br><br>
</div></td></tr>

<tr><td width="80px" valign="top"><h1 class="h1_gray">Step 6: </h1></td>
<td><div>Review your work with a tutor.<br><br>
</div></td></tr>

</table>
</td></tr>
         
<tr><td><div>

<h1 class="h1_gray">That's it. You are done! Thank you for completing this guided learning activity.</h1>
